USDA has allowed a nationwide waiver to allow school meals to be served to ALL students for free for a short time period as a result of COVID-19. Effective Monday, September 14, 2020 ALL Edinburgh Community School Corp students who want can eat one breakfast and one lunch FREE per school day through December 31, 2020, unless federal funds run out before that date. Students will continue to pay for a la carte items, second trays, and extra milk. If a student brings their lunch and wants milk they will be charged $.50 unless they take a free meal tray. Adults will still need to pay for their meals.

This institution is an equal opportunity provider.

post_text:
Stop Means Stop!
If a school bus is at a full stop with stop signs out and lights blaring, it means to STOP! This is the most crucial point in school bus safety, as kids are exiting and entering the bus, and they may not be aware of other vehicles on the road. When even adults have issues with looking both ways before crossing the street, it’s no surprise that children have problems remembering that as well.

You MUST stop if the bus stops, and resume moving when the bus deems it appropriate

*Originally posted by the Antlers Police Department fin Oklahoma*

post_text:
Edinburgh Community Schools' parents, students,and staff members.

It was brought to my attention this evening by Mr.Kevin Rockey, Principal of Edinburgh High School, and Mrs.Allison Small, Corporation Nurse, that a second high school student has tested positive for the corona virus.

They have contact traced this student and all students
who were within six feet of him for over fifteen minutes. Those students have been quarantined for fourteen days.

As I said before, we will follow our COVID-19 Re-entry Plan that directs us to address positive cases on a case-by-case basis.

We will continue to monitor the number of students impacted by this virus and will make decisions regarding instruction in compliance with CDC and
Johnson County Board of Health recommendations.

As always, our greatest concern is the health and wellness of all of our staff members and students.

If you have questions about this, please feel free to call or e-mail me.

Thank you.
Dr. Doug Arnold, Superintendent

All-Call to Edinburgh Community Schools’ parents and students.

Good evening, this your superintendent of schools, Dr. Doug Arnold.

I want to inform you that a student at Edinburgh High School has tested positive for the corona virus. Mr.Rockey, EHS Principal, and Mrs. Allison Small, Corporation Nurse, investigated this matter and spoke with the Johnson County Health Department. All recommendations are being followed and there is no reason for concern.

The Edinburgh Community Schools will continue following our COVID-19 Re-entry Plan that directs us to handle COVID-19 on a case-by-case basis. This is what we intend to do.

If you have any questions, please feel free to speak to Mrs. Small, Mr. Rockey or myself.

As always, our greatest concern is the health and wellness of all of our staff members and students.

Edinburgh Community High School and the Lancer Athletic Department regrets they will not be able to sell season athletic passes for this coming school year. Nor will they be able to honor Senior Citizen passes or free passes on Lancer Discount Cards. Due to the State of Indiana guidelines on public gatherings caused by the Covid-19 virus, the number of fans admitted to contests has to be monitored to stay at the percentages allowed and also to allow for contact tracing.

All spectators will be required to pay the regular ticket price to be admitted and fans will be turned away after the maximum number of attendees has been reached. The Athletic Department would like to apologize in advance for the inconvenience and look forward to returning to the normal Season Pass and Senior Citizen program in the 2021-2022 school year.

July 7 at 12:11 PM ·

PRE-K AND KINDERGARTEN DRIVE-THROUGH REGISTRATION INSTRUCTIONS
East Side Elementary

Here is all the information you need to know for our upcoming Kindergarten Registration. Due to the COVID-19 regulations, this registration will be conducted with a Drive-Through process at East Side Elementary from 9:00 am until 2:00 pm on Tuesday, July 14, and Thursday, July 16. Please read the information below before coming to the Registration line. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (812) 526-9771.

REGISTRATION PACKETS & INSTRUCTIONS

-Registration packets will be handed out as you pull up to the main entrance.
-Copies of Birth Certificates will be made while you fill out the registration packet.
-Registrations for pre-kindergarten will be processed in the order they are received.
-Please do not park and get out of your car. Stay in the line and a member of our staff will come to you.
PARKING/LINE-UP
-After you receive your packet, pull up to one of our parking spots and fill it out. One of our staff members will come to pick up your packet.

post_text:
June 30 Deadline Approaching for 21st Century Scholars’ Enrollment
Seventh, Eighth Grade Students Encouraged to Apply

(INDIANAPOLIS) – Indiana seventh and eighth grade students can still apply for the 21st Century Scholars program, but the June 30 deadline is swiftly approaching. Led by the Indiana Commission for Higher Education, 21st Century Scholars (https://learnmoreindiana.org/scholars/) is the state’s early college promise program that provides up to four years of undergraduate tuition and fees for eligible low-income students at Indiana colleges and universities.

To qualify, students must apply during their seventh or eighth grade year. Most students who qualify for the federal free and reduced lunch guidelines will qualify for the 21st Century Scholars program – but students can only take advantage if they apply before the June 30 deadline.

post_text:
East Sides Satellite Launch!

Students, parents and interested parties can watch the signal from the balloon during flight tomorrow and throughout its lifespan. In order to do this you will need to type aprs.fi into your browser. Once the page opens on the top right in the blue area you will see a box that says "Track Call Sign" please enter WB8MSJ-2 into the box and click SEARCH.

Once that is done, a map will display and shortly after launch, once the solar panels collect enough energy, you will see a report from the tracker. The tracker will transmit every 2 minutes on 144.390 MHz.

Second, Many factors contribute to the length of flight. Weather, is the most significant. We have balloons that last anywhere from a day to over 2 weeks. Assuming our satellite doesn't encounter a typhoon, hurricane or other phenomenon, we should stay aloft for some time. Each day, except when over large bodies of water (Atlantic or Pacific) you can log in as described above and see the location of your satellite.

Once that is done, a map will display and shortly after launch, once the solar panels collect enough energy, you will see a report from the tracker. The tracker will transmit every 2 minutes on 144.390 MHz.

Second, Many factors contribute to the length of flight. Weather, is the most significant. We have balloons that last anywhere from a day to over 2 weeks. Assuming our satellite doesn't encounter a typhoon, hurricane or other phenomenon, we should stay aloft for some time. Each day, except when over large bodies of water (Atlantic or Pacific) you can log in as described above and see the location of your satellite.
